<HEAD>Senator Wants Supreme Court to Take Over Impeachment Trials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers who have been tied up by the impeachment trials of three federal judges in as many years are calling for a change in the Constitution to hand such trials to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Wyche </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the 12-member trial committee that heard the case of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> earlier this month, said Friday that he would propose a constitutional amendment to relieve <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of its impeachment duties `` They ought to be the ultimate triers of fact,'' <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> said of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justices. `` They are the most qualified. They have the constitutional perspective on both the protections and sensitivity of federal judgeships,'' he said. He said the justices also have more time for the lengthy process required to remove judges from the federal bench. The amendment would pertain only to the federal judiciary, leaving the trial of other public officials impeached by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, who said he would sponsor the proposal with Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, D-N.Y. An impeachment voted by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> serves as an indictment for trial before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. A two-thirds vote of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is required to then remove an official from office and disqualify the person from holding other federal office. There only have been 15 impeachments by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for trial in the 200-year history of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but three of them have been in the last three years and all of the last three were federal judges. <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> said he spent all of August studying the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> case prior to the four-day trial before his special 12-member committee earlier this month. The full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is expected to take no less than two days to hear the case, debate and vote. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearings in the impeachment case against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> took four weeks last summer and are awaiting action by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The impeachment and trial of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> in 1986 took the committee 10 days to hear and the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> 18 hours to consider before voting to remove <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> from office. According to Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., who was majority leader at the time, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor proceedings took more time than all but a handful of major issues before the 98th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Under the Constitution, the federal judges are appointed for life and can be removed from office only by voluntary resignation, death or trial by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>'s plan for a constitutional amendment is not the first call for a change in the discipline of federal judges. Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kastenmeier </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on courts, intellectual property and the administration of justice, has proposed strengthening federal laws governing the judges and setting up a commission to study the impeachment process
