<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says it does n't really matter that a drug dealer was coaxed into selling crack cocaine near the White House _ just so the president could tell the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people that's where the sale took place. `` The man went there and sold drugs in front of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, did n't he?'' the president told reporters in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> on Friday. `` That's the bottom line. That's what the man did.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> concede the drug dealer was maneuvered into making a previously arranged sale in <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, across the street from the White House. The president displayed the cocaine in a see-through plastic bag in his nationally televised drug strategy speech on Sept. 5. He told the audience the crack had been `` seized a few days ago in a park across the street from the White House.'' A Democratic senator from <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, criticized the president's use of the prop as `` staged.'' `` Is this really a drug war, or is this theatrics and screenplay?'' he asked. `` We do n't need the president to lure drug pushers to <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> for photo opportunities.'' And a reporter suggested to the president that the transaction would n't have taken place in the park had the cocaine not been needed for the speech. `` The message I get out of it -LRB- is -RRB- a man was busted in front of the White House and I can not feel sorry for him,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` He ought not to be out peddling these insidious drugs. It's ruining the children of this country.'' The president said he'd asked for a drug sample `` from that vicinity to show it can happen anywhere ... and that's what they gave me. And they told me where they caught this guy.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke as if the suspected dealer, a teenager, had been arrested. Although the transaction with an undercover <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agent was photographed, the dealer was not taken into custody, agents said, because they hoped he would sell a larger amount later and identify his organization. A planned arrest earlier this week fell through when the suspect did not show up, and agents hope to obtain indictments against him. Asked if the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people were manipulated into thinking drugs were being sold near the White House, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> replied: `` What do you mean it did n't really -LRB- happen -RRB-? The guy was arrested or grabbed for selling drugs in front of the White House. It did n't exist? It did n't happen?'' On every drug bust, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` You bring somebody someplace.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> became irritated with reporters' questions, gesturing toward the press at one point and saying, `` I do n't understand. Are these advocates here for this drug guy?'' But while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> defended the arrangement, another senior <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> official suggested the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> had been `` a little overzealous.'' `` We told them that if a buy could be made near the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, so much the better. They took us literally,'' said the official, asking not to be identified.
