<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice to lead the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> says a measure by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> to stop federal funding of sexually explicit or blasphemous art would cripple the government's role in promoting artistic excellence. `` Making unfettered artistic judgments would be most difficult under the <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> amendment,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frohnmayer </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee considering his nomination. `` I think we need freedom ... and tolerance ... for art to flourish,'' the <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, lawyer told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. The arts agency is at the center of a political storm resulting from the use of federal money in exhibits that included works by artists <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mapplethorpe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mapplethorpe </PERSON>'s photographs depict explicit homosexual acts and <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> displayed a work showing a crucifix submerged in a jar of urine The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in July adopted an amendment by <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, that would prohibit the agency from using any of its $ 170 million in annual appropriations to promote, distribute or produce `` obscene and indecent materials'' or art that denigrates the beliefs of any religion. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted against <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>' measure 264-153 last week after e