<HEAD>FDA Panel Suggests Stronger Warnings on Sleep-Drug Side Effects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal advisory committee says the world's leading sleep medication, Halcion, may put users at greater risk of temporary amnesia than other drugs of its kind <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> panel recommended Friday that the warning be added to Halcion's label and that stronger warnings be given to consumers and doctors about all possible side effects for this drug and other sedative-hypnotics, which are sold only by prescription. The <ORGANIZATION> Psychopharmacological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drugs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to work out the language of the warnings. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Leber </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s division of neuropharmacological drug products, said it would be at least six months before the agency would complete work on the warnings. `` There's no sense of urgency on this,'' he said. <PERSON> Godfrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes Halcion, said the committee's review should put to rest many concerns that have been raised about the drug. The recommendations resulted from the committee's review of a `` relatively high'' number of reports about side effects associated with the use of Halcion compared with other sedative-hypnotics. These included amnesia, anxiety, aggression and hallucinations, all of which are included in the warning label for Halcion. Panel members said the high number of reactions reported may be overstated, since incomplete data on incidents was collected and it can be used only as a broad indicator. `` Given the limitations of the information, we did not sense there was a special problem'' of side effects with Halcion, said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, panel chairman and chief of psychiatric research and psychopharmacology at the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>. Halcion was approved for sale in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1983 and about 43 million prescriptions of the drug have been written since then The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has received 1,693 reports of adverse side effects possibly associated with its use, ranging from amnesia to death, said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Anello </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of epidemiology and biostatistics. By comparison, 35 million prescriptions have been written for Restoril, a sedative-hypnotic made by <ORGANIZATION> Sandoz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, since 1981 and the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has received 266 reports of unwanted side effects, he said. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes Halcion, said the greater number of Halcion reports could be the result of a number of things, including media reports about the drug. These include reports about a <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> woman shot her mother last year after taking Halcion. Charges against the woman were dismissed. <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said the company was `` pleased the advisory committee has essentially come to the conclusion that there are few if any concerns that need to be addressed.'' Besides agreeing to recommend relabeling for Halcion for temporary amnesia, the panel decided to address concerns for the entire class of sleeping pills. Three drugs are included in this class _ Halcion, Restoril and Dalmane. Panel members asked the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to `` provide material to consumers to alert them to the possibility of side effects'' of the drugs so the consumers could discuss them with their doctors. Committee members said they were concerned about `` traveler's amnesia'' _ a temporary syndrome that can affect travelers who take one of the drugs They can function normally after awakening but later wo n't recall their activities during this period, such as going through Customs at the airport. The labels for these drugs already warn of amnesia as a possible side effect, but the committee recommended the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> consider adding `` traveler's amnesia'' to the labels.
