<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many residents of this hurricane-ravaged city mounted bicycles to check on their homes and friends, dodging toppled trees, wind-sheared roofs, broken gas lights and other debris. Hurricane Hugo's torrential rains and 135 mph winds caused an estimated $ 1 billion in damages in historic <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. Mayor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> imposed a 7 p.m. curfew Friday to deter looting, and 1,400 National Guardsmen joined police in patrolling the streets early today. Among those pushing pedals were Dr. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON>, his wife and two daughters. Their golden retriever, `` Snickers,'' maneuvered around the debris on foot. `` We did n't know which streets would be under water,'' said <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Sadlers </ORGANIZATION> spent Thursday night in <LOCATION> Summerville </LOCATION>, about 25 miles inland, when it became clear <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> would get the brunt of Hugo. The family returned to the battered city Friday morning to check on damage, finding streets littered with planks, window frames, shards of glass and other debris. Many of the city's historic homes were damaged and its big oak trees topped by the force of the storm. `` I could n't imagine it being as bad as they were saying,'' said <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Francie </PERSON>. `` I did n't want to believe it. I cried when I came back into town.'' Attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisdale </PERSON> said he decided to use his 10-speed bicycle because his car was low on gasoline and because some streets were impassable in cars. `` Given the problems with the streets, it's easier and faster in many cases to get around on bicycles,'' he said. In the luggage rack of his bicycle, <PERSON> Tisdale </PERSON> carried a folded blue tarp that had covered his desk during the storm. <PERSON> Tisdale </PERSON> said his office was not damaged, but a friend's roof was gone. <PERSON> Tisdale </PERSON> planned to give the tarp to his friend to cover the gaping hole. Another bicyclist, <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, stopped for a break at a street corner across the street from City Hall, whose metal roof was blown off. `` It's the only way to get around,'' she said. `` I came out to look at family homes. One's water damaged. One's roof is damaged. One's OK, except we'd like to take a bath.'' Ms. <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> said she did n't think <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> would cause such extensive damage. `` Lots of trees are down,'' she said. <PERSON> Katie </PERSON> <PERSON> Crouch </PERSON> peddled along Meeting Street, past damaged motels and shops, to check the homes of friends who had evacuated. `` Everything is in shock right now,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Crouch </PERSON>, a high school junior.
