lected cuts also represented a partial concession to Republican demands. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> told a news conference that Republicans asked for concessions `` and we said, <LOCATION> OK </LOCATION>, we'll do that, but lets beef up that treatment side, that prevention side.'' He and other <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers dismissed the notion that their proposal would weaken defense. `` The administration was unwilling to let a $ 300 billion defense budget bear a less than one-half of one percent cut to beef up the war on drugs,'' Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., told reporters
