 to enact emergency regulations. Yet in his letter to <PERSON> Coler </PERSON>, the governor said conditions at the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> clinic `` are precisely why I have called for increased regulation of abortion clinics to protect the health of women.'' The new rules, <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said, will not be as strict as his proposal for the special session to make private abortion clinics adhere to the same standards as ambulatory care clinics. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said HRS should not be blamed for the problems at the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> clinic, saying the agency does n't have the power at present to uncover them. He said he does n't know whether abortion clinics throughout the state have similar practices. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON>, the governor's chief of operations, said veterinary clinics have more stringent regulations than abortion centers. Neither <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Dunbar </PERSON> would be specific about the kinds of regulations being sought, but both said they would be designed to protect the health of women seeking abortions _ not to restrict their access to an abortion.
