<FIRST>r a PM-Berlin-Appreciation     09-23 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin-Appreciation,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Man Who Created the American Popular Song</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Berlin, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON> created the American popular song. Until <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> began writing after the turn of the century, American music was dominated by <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ English music hall, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, Viennese operetta and Italian opera. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> took native American sounds, such as ragtime, and turned them into huge popular hits like `` Alexander's Ragtime Band'' and `` Everybody's Doin' It Now. When <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON> wrote, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> listened _ for more than 50 years. `` He caught the voices of the people early in this century and held them for longer than anyone else,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimball </PERSON>, musical theater historian, said Friday. From his first song, `` Marie of <LOCATION> Sunny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>,'' in 1907 to his last Broadway show, `` Mr. President,'' in 1962, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s presence was felt on the music scene in this country. No one today can look to such a long period of domination. And <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> was a winner in every medium he tried. He found success not only in Tin Pan Alley but on Broadway with musicals like `` Annie Get Your Gun,'' `` Call Me Madam'' and his Music Box revues, and in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> where he wrote the scores for <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Astaire-Ginger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> movies like `` Top Hat'' and `` Follow the Fleet'' and other films like `` Holiday Inn'' and `` Easter Parade.'' His colleagues thought he was the best, particularly contemporaries like <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Kern </PERSON>. He had an enormous influence on the Broadway composers who followed him, especially <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> who relished his inventive way with rhythm. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> also had an incredible versatility, a great intelligence and perspective about the world. He could write any kind of song _ a stirring, patriotic anthem like `` God Bless <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' a seasonal standard like `` White Christmas,'' a comic theater ditty like `` Doin' What Comes Natur ` lly,'' an unbashedly sentimental favorite like `` Always'' or a complex love song like `` Let's Face the Music and Dance `` He was a folk singer and he was able to absorb whatever was happening in the street and bring it out, even more than <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Jablonski </PERSON>, a good friend of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s and the author of several books on American theater composers. `` He was an ordinary man who was able to write songs. That's why he appealed so much to people. `` But he also made a point of not being a well-educated musician. He was a born musician, which is a hard thing to be. So he could be more sophisticated that he ever thought he was.'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> also was a shrewd businessman. He was a charter member and served on the first board of directors for <ORGANIZATION> ASCAP </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Composers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Authors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION>, which collects songwriting royalties. Before 1920, he had formed his own music publishing company which published all of his music. And at the time of his death, he was still co-owner of the Music Box Theater, a Broadway theater he built in 1921. As late as two years ago, he would call up the box office at the Music Box to see how the grosses were going. But it will be for his music that he will be remembered. `` I would think <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> is the most admired songwriter <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has produced in this century _ and maybe ever,'' <PERSON> Kimball </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
