<HEAD>Barrier Islands off South Carolina Devastated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FOLLY BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane Hugo's six-hour blast left <LOCATION> Folly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> unrecognizable even to its mayor. Up the coast, the storm's wake left two other barrier islands cut off, and sliced another in two. Folly Beach, the town and island just south of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, virtually lost its entire beachfront row of homes. `` I do n't know where we are,'' Mayor <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Linville </PERSON> said during a tour of the area. `` All of my usual landmarks are gone.'' One missing dwelling was the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Restaurant, which had survived years of serious erosion that left it literally sitting atop pilings in the ocean, approachable only by foot bridge. After <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>, all that remained was its red shingle roof. `` About 30 percent of the houses on the island are no longer habitable, if they're even here,'' said <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Folly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Linville </PERSON> estimated the damage at tens of millions of dollars and said hundreds of buildings had been damaged or destroyed. Most of the seaward houses in the town of 2,000 residents either were cracked open or without roofs or windows. Along the ocean, support poles for beach houses had nothing to support, their houses having been washed away by <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s 12 - to 17-foot tidal surge <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, about 50 feet from the ocean, looked like a dirt road, covered with sand and the debris of smashed beach houses. The storm showed that the destruction was often a game of chance. One house was knocked off its foundation and with a wall missing. But a china cabinet remained standing as did two plates inside. Demolished houses spewed mattresses, clothes, and furniture along the beach. The Holiday Inn, which sits on a slab of concrete 50 feet from the ocean, seemed to weather the storm remarkably well despite its proximity to the ocean. Its upper floors remained intact even though the first floor was demolished. Farther up the coast, two barrier islands _ <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and the Isle of Palms _ were cut off from land because the storm knocked out its only link _ the swing-span <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridge </PERSON>. On the Isle of Palms, which hosts the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Clay Court Tennis Championships, the hurricane ripped the fishing pier out of the water and destroyed million-dollar waterfront homes. About 100 boats that had been docked at the Wild Dunes Marina were `` stacked up like cordwood'' across the marina on <LOCATION> Goat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Moise </PERSON>, a state Wildlife and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> created a 100 - to 200-foot-wide channel of water through <LOCATION> Pawleys </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, midway between <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Sellers </PERSON>, a pilot from <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> who flew people to the coast to check their property `` There are now two <LOCATION> Pawleys </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, if you will,'' Sellers said. Back on Folly Beach, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> DuBani </PERSON> walked along the streets Friday afternoon carrying a small satchel and looking for a ride. While many other heeded evacaution orders before the storm, <PERSON> DuBani </PERSON> said he remained and partied with some other people in an ocean front house as <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> smashed ashore. `` It was incredible,'' he said. `` Everything was just floating by.'' <PERSON> DuBani </PERSON> said he left the house when it began breaking up, and walked across the street to a neighbor's house whose door had been blown open. `` I got scared and just grabbed my clothes. This is all I have left,'' he said, pointing to his pouch that contained a fishing pole, a can of beer, some swimming fins, a snorkel, several shirts and a few pairs of pants. `` Thinking about heading to <LOCATION> Key </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>,'' he said before hitching a ride out of town with a blonde woman in a sports car. But <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Tetric </PERSON> was determined to stay. `` Going to rebuild,'' he said of his demolished house. `` I pay taxes, and, if I pay taxes, I should have full use of my property.''
