<HEAD>Siegfried and Roy Open Lavish Magic Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The magic tricks, dazzling and amazing, flow one into the next. A mime troupe sparks children's laughter, while a basketball game on unicycles draws chortles from adults. Walking through a green light that appears to have no ramp beneath it, <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> opened the first of 32 performances at Radio City Music Hall on Friday night, a show as lavish in constuming and lighting as those the late <PERSON> Liberace </PERSON> used to do. <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> are swallowed by two robots helped by putty-colored people with big insect heads. A woman arrives, lifts her arms and disappears. Another woman is seen swimming in a tank. A cloth is thrown over the tank and when it's removed, a white tiger is in there and the audience hears a tape-recorded roar. That all takes place in the first few minutes of the show, and <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> are n't taking time to milk the applause. Their show is so fast-paced the viewer has time only to gasp before the next dazzlement. Women assistants suffer everything but being sawed in half. One lies in a long box which is pushed together like an accordion. Another swings on a swing from her waist up. Her skirt, legs and feet dance out on stage separately. Another gets into a Japanese box, which then is folded into a tiny square box. Unfolded into a large rectangle again, she emerges from it. Another is balanced on a spike, which seems then to skewer her. The charming <PERSON> Mummenschanz </PERSON> mime troupe from <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> was a special favorite with children. A big green `` clam'' licks its lips around a stuffed rabbit before gobbling it up. Two men wearing putty masks made countless shapes with them, one pulling a pieces of the `` face'' out like chewing gum and whacking it back onto himself. The unicycle basketball teams are the King Charles Troupe, formed in the 1960s as a <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> unicycle club. There are a couple of Las Vegas-style numbers by dancers wearing not much. The animals are beautiful. A white car drives on stage _ as <ORGANIZATION> Liberace </ORGANIZATION> used to do _ bringing a mother white tiger and three cubs. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> rides an elephant, which disappears, then reappears. At the end, a 650-pound white tiger climbs atop a globe. With <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> on his back, they're pulled into the air. It's a <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> show and it's nonstop entertainment. New Yorkers are n't too sophisticated for this.
