pvs, `We buy...' ^By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PURSAT, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ravaged by two decades of war and bloody revolution, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> now faces a drought that is expected to cut rice and fish cultivation by 25 percent and threaten many with starvation. A lack of local government to provide social services or otherwise help people makes the prospects for this nation of 8 million appear even bleaker. `` If the war wo n't kill you then you might die because of no water,'' said <PERSON> Treang </PERSON> <PERSON> Suon </PERSON>, a 37-year-old mother of four from Veal village in the <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> province, 90 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>. `` And there is no government to help us along.'' Interviews with peasants, government officials, teachers and Western aid officials in the provinces of <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kampong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chhnang </LOCATION> gave a dark picture of the future for <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The country appears poised to slide into a new phase of civil conflict now that the Vietnamese, this nation's occupiers for the last decade, say they will withdraw the last of their troops by Tuesday. Fighting between <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> government troops and guerrillas from the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> resistance group already is intensifying in <LOCATION> Battambang </LOCATION>, 140 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION>. A Western doctor in <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> said his hospital has seen a twofold increase in gunshot wounds over the past two months. `` Now we average about five a day,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> are moving about very freely and the peasants are scared.'' The economy, too, is in deep trouble. Fish cultivation and timber production have fallen in <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> for two straight years. Due to the late and light rains this year, production of rice, the staple crop for the whole country, also is sure to fall. Three decades of peace ended in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in 1970 when a military coup ousted Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, dragging <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> into the Vietnam War. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> took power in 1975 and killed hundreds of thousands of people under their radical brand of agrarian communism. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded the country in December 1978 and installed a pro-Hanoi regime in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>. A resistance coalition led by <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> has been battling the Vietnamese and Cambodian government troops. If the economy worsens, the government will lose legitimacy, making its battle against the resistance front that much harder. The biggest loser will be <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s people. Time was when the Moslem people of <PERSON> Ro </PERSON> <PERSON> Leap </PERSON> village took the half-day walk over palm-lined paths and verdant paddies to <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tonle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sap </ORGANIZATION> to fish the once-bountiful waters. But now there is a drought, and bands of <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas would make a trip too risky. `` We buy our fish now and only eat it on special occasions,'' said <PERSON> Ty </PERSON> <PERSON> Chouk </PERSON>, a 37-year-old farmer. `` We used to fish everyday.'' The catch in <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> province fell 41 percent between 1987 and 1988 to 4,120 metric tons, according to <PERSON> Khang </PERSON> <PERSON> Heang </PERSON>, vice chief of the provincial committee. Another drop in 1989 is expected, government officials said. They still fish in nearby Veal village, but the residents no longer wander into the forest near Ro Leap to cut hardwood timber and bamboo for their homes. Landmines laid by the government and the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> have blown up too many people. `` The folks near the lake do n't come up here anymore,'' <PERSON> Ty </PERSON> <PERSON> Chouk </PERSON> said. `` Only we know where the government mines are because we laid them in the ground. Other villages are too scared to risk their lives. Even we do n't go into the high areas anymore. That belongs to the Pol Pot people and their mines.'' Timber cultivation also fell in <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> between 1987 and 1988, dropping 16 percent to 5,000 cubic meters, <PERSON> Khang </PERSON> <PERSON> Heang </PERSON> said. Bad weather has been another problem. Scarce rain pushed rice planting back from May until August, raising doubts as to whether the peasants around <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> would be able to plant a second crop of rice. `` My family will go hungry this year,'' said Mrs. Suon, spitting a red wad of beetlenut juice in the dirt. `` We ca n't live only on coconuts and onions, we must have rice.'' Another blow to agriculture has been the government's policy to forcibly conscript many young men. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Poen </LOCATION>, a 43-year-old father of four, had his two sons taken away by the military. `` They were rounded up after a movie show,'' he said. `` It is good that they are serving the country but I need them, too, to farm the fields. I had to drop some land this year and am farming less. So we will have too little to eat.'' <PERSON> Khang </PERSON> <PERSON> Heang </PERSON> estimated that rice cultivation in <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION> would fall between 12 percent and 25 percent. `` If the weather does n't get better the people could starve,'' he said. A <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> official said he believed nationwide production would probably fall 25 percent. Yet another problem is the lack of local administration to help people deal with the crisis. At Veal village, which is responsible for eight communes holding about 1,500 people, the local government office consists of a ramshackle two-story house. Three rooms open onto a courtyard shaded by coconut trees. Freshly painted signs, `` Justice,'' `` Administration'' and `` Economy'' hang from the rooms. `` These are our departments,'' says <PERSON> Hem </PERSON> <PERSON> Pheach </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> official. The rooms contain no chairs or tables. There is no paper, no phone. In one room, a chicken clucks in a corner, searching for food. `` We lack some materials,'' Hem says quietly, `` then maybe we can get on with our job.''
