 the island. He said the National Guard was operating at 40 percent strength and the police at 80 percent. Ms. <PERSON> Belardo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neal </PERSON> said she and four other senators met with Gov. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrelly </PERSON> on Friday to find out when people can expect relief supplies. The <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Croix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> vice chairman, <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Crittenden </PERSON>, complained that the army failed to promptly fly in food, clothes, bedding and medicine. `` Here we are, and this is what I have,'' she said, pointing to some old clothes piled on a table and the floor of an office. <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON> said federal disaster specialists arrived on St. Croix Tuesday but were unable to request immediate help because of communications problems. He said the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> needs `` everything from wrenches to chain saws to medical supplies.'' In <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, 70 percent of the island's 3.3. million residents remained without running water and 20,000 were still housed in shelters Large parts of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, the capital, and several towns in the northeast also remained without power, officials said. Hundreds of residents in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> stood in long lines waiting for water, ice and gasoline. When Gov. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> arrived in the northern coastal town of <LOCATION> Canovanas </LOCATION> on Friday to inspect local shelters, angry residents complained they had received no govenment aid since the storm. `` We're all in the street. We do n't have any food, water or light. Our houses blew away,'' resident <PERSON> Gladys </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> told the governor. In the British colony of <LOCATION> Montserrat </LOCATION>, Gov. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said 30 percent of the homes will have to be rebuilt and another 30 percent will need extensive repairs. He said about 3,000 of the island's 12,500 residents were left homeless. While the 39-square-mile island still lacked power, some water and phone service was being restored, he said.
