<HEAD>Chinese Students Argue For Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Chinese students seeking asylum testified that a return to their homeland would mean a life as bleak as their families endured during <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Cultural Revolution. The students, who fled to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> after leading an anti-government protest in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> following the June crackdown in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, were emotional Friday during the first day of their hearing. Asked through a Cantonese translator if she would be willing to return to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Li </PERSON> replied, `` I would rather die.'' The 27-year-old linguistics student testified about her father's imprisonment during the Cultural Revolution and her own fears that her political activity while studying in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would lead her to the same fate `` If we return, it's like a death row. My life will be like my father's and many others','' she said. Her fiance, <PERSON> Luo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jian </PERSON> <PERSON> Guang </PERSON>, said when his father died last July, he was afraid to return for the funeral. `` I would never return to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> because if I return to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, they know my name, they will imprison me,'' he said. The students were led handcuffed into the court, but federal Immigration Judge <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hornbach </PERSON> ordered the handcuffs removed. Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> had no particular position on the matter but filed a brief containing a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> recommendation that asylum not be granted because the students had n't proved they face persecution if they return to <LOCATION> Chin