<HEAD>Three Nobel Academy Members Quit, Two Cite Rushdie Affair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three members of the academy that awards the Nobel Prize for literature have resigned, and two said they were unhappy that the body did not denounce <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s death threat against <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>. The secretary of the Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sture </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, confirmed Thursday he received three letters of resignation but said they could not be accepted because the academy's 200-year-old rules stipulate that members are elected for life. Author <PERSON> Kerstin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ekman </PERSON>, one of the three to resign from the 18-member body, told Swedish radio afterward, `` No human can, at least in our country, belong to an organization which she does not want to be part of. ... I guess they just can not admit that we quit.'' In any case, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the resignations will not affect the work of the academy. He declined further comment. The third resigning member, poet <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspenstrom </PERSON>, did not disclose his reasons but told Swedish television his motives differed from those of his two colleagues. The resignations came weeks before the announcement of the winner of the Nobel Prize for literature. The date is not set in advance but traditionally falls in October. In explaining her reasons for resigning, Ms. <PERSON> Ekman </PERSON> said, `` I am upset about the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> affair.'' She and another resigning colleague, former <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Lars </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyllensten </PERSON>, stopped taking part in the academy's work in February. They said they were protesting because the academy refused to condemn explicitly the death threat issued Feb. 14 by the late <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> blasphemed Islam in his novel, `` The Satanic Verses,'' a bestseller that stirred worldwide protests among Moslems. Several other Academy members have complained about the group's stand on the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> case but generally accepted its tradition of avoiding official statements on political issues Ms. <PERSON> Ekman </PERSON> said the three resigning members had not planned their action together. She said she had submitted a resignation now to let a substitute be elected. She also said the Academy was in need of renewal. `` Everybody realizes that it has come to a standstill,'' she said. The Academy statutes were written by <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustaf </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who founded the institution in 1786. It has awarded the prestigious Nobel Prize for literature since 1901.
