<HEAD>Chest Pains Subsided But Condition Still Serious, Doctor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nobel laureate <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> was still in serious condition although the fever and the chest pains she suffered for more than two weeks had subsided, her doctor said today. `` But her condition is not critical,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Rajen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wats </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Woodlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nursing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Home </LOCATION>, the hospital where the 79-year-old Roman Catholic nun was admitted Sept. 5 with a high fever and irregular heartbeat. <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>'s condition twice become critical after she suffered a heart attack in the hospital's intensive care unit Sept. 8 and occasional chest pains since then. `` We will have to observe her for two more weeks before we can say if she is out of danger or not,'' <ORGANIZATION> Wats </ORGANIZATION> said. Doctors have said that after she leaves the hospital, <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> will have to give up the hectic schedule that is partly blamed for her illness. Despite poor health in recent years, she has traveled widely to help the destitute and the dying, work that earned her a Nobel Peace Prize in 1979.
