<HEAD>Police Use Barbed Wire to Stop Women's March; White Supremacists
Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 200 arrested, including white supremacist,
Winnie Mandela ordered to leave Pretoria, ABC reporter detained. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police blocked entrances to the capital today and strung barbed wire down a main street to stop an unauthorized march by anti-apartheid women's groups. Organizers said about 200 people were arrested. Police also used batons to clear black bystanders from <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>'s central square after scuffles broke out when right-wing whites in swastika-marked khaki uniforms began hustling blacks away from the site of an approved pro-apartheid rally One white right-winger and several blacks were arrested. The white extremists had received permission for their rally, but the women's planned march to government headquarters was banned because organizers refused to apply for a permit. The church where marchers were to meet was blocked off with rolls of barbed wire and guarded by scores of police officers. <PERSON> Zeni </PERSON> <PERSON> Tshongweni </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the march organizers, said about 200 people were arrested when they tried to assemble near the Union Buildings, the government headquarters which was the intended destination of the march. She said several people were injured when police used whips and dogs to disperse the crowd. Police detained <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergay </PERSON>, correspondent for the American television network <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, and several other journalists. Two buses, carrying <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, wife of imprisoned <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, and other blacks were chased through the streets by about 25 yellow police vehicles with sirens screaming and lights flashing. The police stopped the buses and ordered Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and the other occupants to leave <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. `` We came here peacefully but they are seeking violence,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is the same as any other country in the world. People ca n't break the law,'' said Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, standing among riot police behind the barbed wire that blocked the entrance to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alban </LOCATION>'s Anglican Cathedral A two-page notice was tacked to the door of the church, saying the government obtained a court order to stop a church service and the planned march to the Union Buildings. Two tear gas cannon trucks were parked nearby and hundreds of police lined the streets as the city center came to a standstill. The government banned the march because the organizers refused to ask for official permission, although women's groups said they had notified top government officials including President F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> and talked with <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> traffic police. The government granted permission for two white supremacist groups to hold rallies two blocks from the cathedral because they had sought permission, officials said. At the first rally a banner called for the hanging of <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and for the release from prison of <PERSON> Barend </PERSON> <PERSON> Strydom </PERSON>, a white former policeman convicted early this year of killing seven black people in a shooting spree in the center of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. As the meeting ended, an altercation began when about 40 blacks tried to walk across the square where the rally was held and were stopped by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Afrikaner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, who wear khaki uniforms and use swastika symbols. Police began herding away the blacks, who were flashing peace signs, and calling out to the whites, `` Peace, we all have the same blood.'' Suddenly police began running through the square, arresting blacks, letting their dogs loose and ordering reporters and everyone else from the area. It was not immediately clear whether the second right-wing rally would be allowed to go ahead. Organizers of the women's march said police blocked almost all traffic from the black townships around <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. Traffic was backed up from <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>'s main thoroughfare to the freeway leading north from <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> as police at roadblocks stopped and searched buses and cars filled with women and turned them away. About 30,000 women had been expected to defy the ban and try to march. About 200 women, most of them white, made their way to a park at the bottom of the ridge where the Union Buildings stand, but police arrived and ordered them to leave. They did not move quickly enough and several were arrested. A.R. <PERSON> Dawood </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> said police hit some of the women with their batons. In obtaining a court order against the women's march, lawyers for the police had argued that the proximity of the right-wing rallies might lead to conflict. The women's groups said they had made extensive arrangements, including training parade marshals and setting up first-aid stations, to ensure their march was peaceful. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 28 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate neighborhoods, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
