<HEAD>Russian Cantor's Son Who Became Essence of America Music Dead at
101</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 20th graf, `Composer Burt...', to CORRECT name of song
to `Raindrops Keep Fallin' sted Are Falling...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY5, NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERENA DOBNIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON>, the Russian cantor's son whose songs such as `` Cheek to Cheek,'' `` Easter Parade,'' `` White Christmas'' and `` God Bless America'' became the essence of American music, has died at age 101. `` He's been so much a part of all of us, of all ages, over all the many years,'' said composer-conductor <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Composers </ORGANIZATION>, Authors and Publishers. Of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s music, <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> said: `` It's become part of our language, part of our heartbeat, part of our soul. `` It's the kind of finish of an era.'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> died in his sleep at his <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> town house Friday afternoon, said his son-in-law, <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>. Asked if <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> had been ill, <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> said, `` No, he was 101 years old. ... He just fell asleep.'' An actor, singer, and songwriter, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> began his career in the early days of vaudeville and his songs for a time so dominated the stage and screen that the late composer, <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Kern </PERSON>, said: `` <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> has no place in American music. He is American music.'' In a musical career that began with a job as a singing waiter, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> wrote nearly 1,000 songs, from his first big hit, `` <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s Ragtime Band'' in 1911, to `` Puttin' on the Ritz,'' which was revived in 1983 by the Dutch singer <PERSON> Taco </PERSON> and was a hit on the rock charts. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> was an immigrant Russian whose `` God Bless America'' became the nation's unofficial second national anthem. A Jew, his `` White Christmas'' and `` Easter Parade'' became Christian holiday traditions. `` American music was born at his piano,'' violinist <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s 100th birthday. So timeless was his appeal that his songs have become hits over and over, performed by such artists as <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>, Barbra Streisand and <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> ASCAP </ORGANIZATION> records show 25 of his songs have topped the popular music charts. `` Blue Skies,'' a top hit when he penned it in 1926, reached the charts again 51 years later on an album by country singer <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> played the piano by ear and never stopped making what he described as `` songs with heart.'' Even in his 90s, he talked of adding yet another musical to his credits, which included 19 stage musicals and 15 movie scores. At his peak, one smash followed another so readily that <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> once said <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> `` ca n't help but write hits.'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, along with 11 other <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> immigrants, received a medal from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> during the Statue of Liberty centennial celebrations in July 1986. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> the actor was featured in the mammoth, flag-waving 1943 movie musical `` This is the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>,'' with songs from <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> and I are deeply saddened by the death of a wonderfully talented man whose musical genius delighted and stirred millions, and will live on forever,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. Always a private man, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> declined to attend a Carnegie Hall gala, led by <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>, to mark his 100th birthday on May 11, 1988. He was mourned by artists from across the spectrum of American music. `` <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> was the greatest Tin Pan Alley songwriter,'' said opera singer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON>, who also sings <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s songs. `` He was not a great musician but he had a great ear and he had a feeling for melody and words that was precious.'' Composer <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacharach </PERSON>, who wrote the 1969 Academy Award-winning song `` Raindrops Keep Fallin' on My Head'' said, `` This is a great loss. But <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON> has left us with the greatest legacy through his music.'' `` One could hear the dancing by just singing the lyrics,'' cabaret singer <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Short </PERSON> said. `` He is perhaps the last of the giants _ and I think that's not a bad way to go.'' Actress and dancer <PERSON> Ginger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> remembered <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> with a bit of song from his `` Cheek to Cheek,'' from the movie `` Top Hat.'' `` I'm in heaven,'' she sang, then broke off. `` It was like heaven,'' she said, describing the thrill of working with the likes of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Astaire </PERSON>. The biggest names on Broadway played in his musical successes, which began in the World War I era with `` Watch Your Step,'' starring <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Castle </PERSON>, and ran through such post-World War II hits as `` Annie Get Your Gun'' and `` Call Me Madam,'' both with <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Merman </PERSON>. `` A Pretty Girl Is Like A Melody,'' one of many <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> wrote for the Ziegfeld Follies, became the unofficial theme song for every Ziegfeld extravaganza. In <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> did the scores of `` Top Hat,'' starring <PERSON> Astaire </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>; `` Holiday Inn'' with <PERSON> Astaire </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bing </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON>; `` Blue Skies''; `` Easter Parade''; `` White Christmas''; and `` There's No Business Like Show Business.'' His last Broadway show was `` Mr. President'' in 1962. His last song, `` An Old Fashioned Wedding,'' was published in 1966. His music-publishing empire earned him a fortune, which he readily shared with his country in wartime or with favorite causes. Since 1939 the Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> have been getting the royalties from `` God Bless America.'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> was awarded three medals for his works and a special <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> award for his contribution to the musical theater. He won a congressional medal for the acclaimed World War II musical, `` This is the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>,'' and the Academy Award for best song of 1942 for `` White Christmas.'' Explaining the seemingly endless gusher of successful songs, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> said his tunes were merely rewrites of a handful of his best numbers. `` All good songwriters have no more than half a dozen good tunes in their systems, and if they have that many they're liberally blessed,'' he once said. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> never learned to read or write music and his piano playing was confined to the key of F sharp. He called songwriting hard work, but director <PERSON> Josh </PERSON> <PERSON> Logan </PERSON> once recalled that <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> dashed off the first verse of `` Anything You Can Do I Can Do Better'' during a six-minute cab ride. Celebrity and wealth did n't seem to touch the shy personality of the intense, short man with wavy, slicked-down hair and dark glasses. He lived a simple life, centered on his songwriting and his family _ his late wife, <PERSON> Ellin </PERSON>, and their three daughters. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> was brought up in poverty amid the immigrant swarm on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s Lower East Side. Born <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baline </ORGANIZATION> on May 11, 1888, he was 5 when his family emigrated from <LOCATION> Temun </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. He was one of eight children and acquired his earliest musical education from his father, a cantor. But his father's death put an end to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s formal education and, at age 8, he went from the second grade to the streets to earn a living. Known as <PERSON> Izzy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> sold newspapers, guided a blind, singing beggar and worked in vaudeville. In 1907, he wrote the words to his first song, `` Marie of Sunny <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'' in collaboration with the piano player at the <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> bar where he worked as a singing waiter. The song earned him 37 cents in royalties and a new name _ the sheet music cover erroneously credited the words to `` I. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>.'' In 1911, at the age of 23, he was contributing songs to the Ziegfeld Follies. His `` <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s Ragtime Band'' with its `` ragged meter'' ushered jazz onto the popular scene and established <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> as a master of Tin Pan Alley. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s marriage to <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> the following year ended after six months when his bride died of typhoid contracted during their honeymoon in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. In his grief, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> composed `` When I Lost You.'' His marriage in 1926 to <PERSON> Ellin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> followed one of the most widely reported courtships of the decade. His wife's father, a prominent Roman Catholic layman and head of <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, had opposed the union. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s wife died of a stroke at age 85 in July 1988. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> is survived by his three daughters, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>. Services will be private, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartgrove </PERSON>, evening manager at the <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> funeral home in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>.
