<DATELINE>BILBAO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Basque separatist group <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility today for the parcel bombing death of the owner of a fish store in this northern city and said it had mistaken the man for a policeman. In a statement published in the radical Basque newspaper Egin, <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> said the killing Sept. 12 was `` an irreparable error and mistake'' and apologized to the victim's family. <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> claimed the bomb was intended for a policeman who used the name of the dead man as a cover, but added: `` The sole responsibility is ours for this death.'' <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Reina </PERSON> <PERSON> Mesonera </PERSON> died of injuries suffered when a parcel he received in the mail exploded as he tried to open it, police said. <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> seeks independence from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> for the three-province northern Basque region. In its 21-year campaign of violence, <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600 people, including 13 so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> recently claimed responsibility for a parcel bomb that killed a prison guard's mother Aug. 11 and for another parcel bomb sent to a Basque businessman Sept. 5 that was detected and safely detonated. On Wednesday, a parcel bomb explosion killed a postman in the Basque city of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sebastian </LOCATION>. No group claimed responsibility, but Interior Minister <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Corcuera </PERSON> told SER radio today that <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> was probably responsible. ETA is an acronym for Basque Land and <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> in the Basque language.
