<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The red star, the symbol of Communist rule in the Soviet bloc for four decades, will be removed from all public buildings in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to reflect the country's move to a multiparty democracy. Government spokesman <PERSON> Zsolt </PERSON> <PERSON> Bajnok </PERSON> told reporters Friday the time had come to replace the red star with the Hungarian coat of arms. `` In previous decades, the symbols of the working class movement were widely used, but now state symbols will take their place on public buildings,'' he said. <PERSON> Bajnok </PERSON> did not say exactly when the red star will be removed from the top of <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>'s sprawling Parliament building. He said removal of the huge symbol would be quite expensive, involving the use of helicopters. Currently the red star decorates all Hungarian public buildings, including government ministries, radio and television, regional and local government buildings and factories.
