<HEAD>Pope Visits Maximum Security Prison for Mafiosi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOLTERRA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> today visited a maximum security prison for Mafia criminals, blessing the inmates and urging them to break free from their `` moral chains.'' The pope, who is on a three-day tour of <LOCATION> Tuscany </LOCATION>, said he was a `` brother among brothers'' with the 150 convicts housed in the 15th century fortress prison that sits atop this medieval hill town. Known as the Fortezza -LRB- fort -RRB-, the prison was a castle begun by <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Brienne </PERSON>, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, in 1343 and completed by <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> the Magnificent in 1472. It has been used as a prison since 1848. Prison officials said most of the inmates were convicted of belonging to organized crime syndicates such as the Sicilian Mafia, <ORGANIZATION> Neapolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Camorra </ORGANIZATION> and Calabrian ` ndrangheta Many were convicted of murder, and 15 are serving life sentences. The inmates clapped and sang as the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> entered the prison courtyard. The area, enclosed by iron bars, normally serves as space for the inmates to play sports. Many prisoners bowed and kissed <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s ring as he walked down the carpeted aisle and patted them on the head. `` Here I am among you, brother among brothers,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said, `` for a visit looked forward to not only by you, but also by me for the affection that I bring you, to people who wish to reconcile themselves with society and find a new place to collaborate constructively for the common good.'' `` There is a liberation of physical chains, which for human beings certainly has great importance, as you can testify. But there is also ... a liberation from moral chains.'' The <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said he was praying that the inmates show `` perseverance in your desire to collaborate in the construction of a free and just society.'' Before the pope spoke, a 26-year-old murder convict gave the pope a welcoming speech. `` Your salute and your blessing are very important for making us accept ourselves and making us accepted by the whole community,'' said <PERSON> Rocco </PERSON> <PERSON> Morano </PERSON>, serving a 21-year sentence for murder in <LOCATION> Calabria </LOCATION>. `` This meeting is a turning point of redemption for all of us.'' It was the third time <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> has visited an Italian prison. In December 1983, he went to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s Rebibbia prison to forgive <PERSON> Mehmet </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Agca </PERSON>, the Turkish gunman who shot him in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s Square in 1981. The pope has also visited the prison in <LOCATION> Civitavecchia </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. The pope celebrated Mass in <LOCATION> Voleterra </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> dei Priori, bordered by medieval mansions, before heading for nearby <LOCATION> Lucca </LOCATION>. On Sunday he will visit <LOCATION> Pisa </LOCATION> before returning to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>.
