ho negotiated mass media reforms during `` round-table'' negotiations this year. <PERSON> Drawicz </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> native, has no significant experience in broadcasting, but he is respected as a journalist and known for his admiration of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policies of perestroika and glasnost, or economic restructuring and openness. Like <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> and thousands of other Solidarity activists, <PERSON> Drawicz </PERSON> was jailed after the 1981 martial-law crackdown on Solidarity. The Communist Party reversed itself this year and agreed to reinstate Solidarity's legal status. Solidarity then scored a landslide victory in June parliamentary elections, enabling it to form a coalition and take control of the government. <PERSON> Drawicz </PERSON> has published many articles both in the state-sanctioned and underground press about the changes taking place in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. He is also a translator of Russian literature. Urban, whom <PERSON> Drawicz </PERSON> replaces, was the chief defender of Communist policies as government spokesman from 1981 until this year.
