 were `` false allegations disseminated by the <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION> government.'' <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> said the executed men all were Kuwaiti nationals, but most were of Iranian, Saudi or Qatari origin. Four other defendants were sentenced to 15 and 20 years in prison and 1,000 to 1,500 whiplashes for the bombings. Another nine people were acquitted. The rulings were made and upheld by lower and appeal courts made up of Islamic scholars. The Iranian spokesman rejected confessions by the condemned men that they were provided with explosives and timing devices by two Iranian officers at the embassy in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Gholoum </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON>. `` Those people were never employed in the Iranian Embassy in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> government is fully aware of this,'' the spokesman said. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> has not commented on the executions. The Iranian spokesman said the attacks were carried out by `` mercenaries working for <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> ... to suppress Moslems who ... reject the Saudi rulers' control of the two holy shrines'' _ Mecca and <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>. Two years ago, he charged, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> pushed pilgrims `` into blood and dust for the crime of disavowing the pagans.'' More than 400 people, mostly Iranians, died in clashes with <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> security forces in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> in 1987. The disturbances were the most serious of a series of incidents during pilgrimages since <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Islamic revolution in 1979, fueled by Iranian efforts to politicize the hajj and encourage other Moslem nations to seize shrines at <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> from the control of the kingdom's <PERSON> Saud </PERSON> royal family. After the violence, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> limited the number of pilgrims and two years ago broke relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, citing subversion and terrorism. Lately, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s new President <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> has indicated he would like to mend the rift. The Iranian spokesman said <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>'s accusations against <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> are part of a campaign by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> Defense Minister Prince <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> and Interior Minister <PERSON> Nayef </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Aziz </PERSON> to keep relations strained. `` This faction strongly desires continuation of enmity,'' it said.
