 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, taking a break today from recreation and work on his <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> speech, called on lawyers to involve themselves in community service and `` protect the unprotected.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in remarks prepared for delivery to a luncheon of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION>, also urged the legal community to work for rights of the unborn in the fight over abortion. `` Use your talents, your energy, and your professional resources to reaffirm the right to life as the most fundamental freedom,'' he said. The president traveled to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> from his vacation home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where he is spending the weekend before heading to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> on Monday. Hitting one of his favorite themes _ the call to community service _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the lawyers in his speech to help the illiterate, the homeless and others in need. `` I challenge you, as <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, not to give in to the dismay of those today, who in the error of alarm have wandered from the basic convictions to which our nation is pledged. I challenge you to rekindle and foster a love of justice.'' `` Part of your task is to use your talents _ to speak for those unable to speak for themselves ... We must remember the unremembered. Protect the unprotected. And stand up for those who live in a world of pain,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. At <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, preparations for his first speech as president to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday were dominating <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s work agenda over the weekend, an administration official said. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the cent