<HEAD>Khmer Rouge, Little Changed, Poised to Strike Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Less than two years after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> withdrew from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas swept in from the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> to unleash one of the most barbaric revolutions of modern times. This month, as <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> withdraws troops that have propped up the Communist government, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> again are poised to strike from the jungles. And many fear that <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> will again become the land of the killing fields. Led by a ruthless Communist with the alias of <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> withstood massive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing and won the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> war with probably no more than 60,000 fighters in 1975. Their opponents _ the government of U.S.-backed <ORGANIZATION> Gen. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nol </ORGANIZATION> _ fielded 300,000 men. The ratio is roughly the same today. <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> strength is estimated at 30,000 to 40,000 and <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>'s at about 150,000. While there are new power brokers in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>, the top <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> leadership remains unchanged. Although the 61-year-old <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> claimed he resigned from his last official post in June, he still is believed to be in firm command. The secretive guerrilla chief, who has refused interviews for 10 years, spends his time along the Thai-Cambodian border and in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the key <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> arms supplier. Other durable veterans are <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>'s right-hand man <PERSON> Ieng </PERSON> <PERSON> Sary </PERSON> and nominal <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Khieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Samphan </PERSON>, whose doctoral thesis was the blueprint for a bloody agrarian revolution. Heading the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> army is <LOCATION> Son </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sen </LOCATION>, who approved the grisly tortures and executions of 20,000 alleged dissidents at <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>'s Tuol Sleng prison during the 1975-78 reign of terror Another key commander is <PERSON> Ta </PERSON> <PERSON> Mok </PERSON>, known as `` The Butcher'' for his murderous ways. These men have admitted to only `` some mistakes,'' and claim to have changed policies and methods. After being driven from <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> by a Vietnamese invasion in January 1979, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> operated from bases along the rugged Thai-Cambodian frontier. From there, its leaders announced they had shed radical Communism in favor of private property, freedom of religion, and a non-aligned foreign policy. It was a dramatic shift _ one met by instant skepticism. In their heydey, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> had `` cleansed the old society'' by killing hundreds of thousands, driving <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks from their monasteries and turning <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> into a slave labor camp where even knives and forks were considered communal property. No mass executions have been reported in Khmer Rouge-controlled areas since 1979. But defectors, international aid workers and human rights groups indicate life under the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> remains slave-like. Beatings and occasional executions are meted out for violating decrees. Women and youngsters are conscripted as porters for the military and forced at times to trek through minefields. Religious worship is permitted only at showcase camps. Contact with foreigners is severely restricted _ to the point of denying the gravely ill medical treatment offered by aid agencies. Perhaps the most damning testimony comes from Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, non-Communist leader of a three-party guerrilla resistance that includes the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. `` One has to be either naive or an idiot to believe that the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> of the 80s can be different from the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> of the 70s,'' he has said. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> _ a term coined by <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> meaning `` Red Cambodians'' _ emerged in the 1960s and began its armed struggle in 1968 as the war in neighboring <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> was reaching a climax. With ideology borrowed from <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> and French leftists, and with support from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s Communists and a segment of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s rural population, the small, ragged band quickly grew into a movement Its initial appeal sprang from real grievances of the peasantry and centuries of humiliation by <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s more powerful neighbors. On April 17, 1975, <ORGANIZATION> Phnom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penh </ORGANIZATION> fell and its more than 2 million people were forced at gunpoint to march into the countryside and plant rice under appalling conditions. For the victors, it was `` Year Zero'' _ the re-making of society from scratch. For most of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s 8 million people it was the beginning of an agony that lasted three years, eight months and 20 days. The defeated <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> army and its civilian followers straggled to the <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> border in 1979, sapped by malaria, hunger and <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s juggernaut. It appeared <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>'s days were numbered. But the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> was saved by geopolitics and international relief aid. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, non-communist <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and others were eager to bring <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to its knees, and the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> was the most readily available instrument. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> provided weapons, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> allowed the use of its territory and the majority of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> member states vote year after year to include the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> as part of the <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> coalition to represent <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> at the world body. Critics charge this is the moral equivalent of inviting <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> to sit in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> after World War II. And Western aid officials struggle with the fact that they kept what some call a monster alive by continuing food, medical and other aid along the Thai-Cambodian border. After 11 years of war and the breakdown of peace talks, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> faces a new turning point. With <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s soldiers still on the way out, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> forces already are testing each other in a major battle for the the gem-rich border town of <LOCATION> Pailin </LOCATION>. Western analysts regard the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> as the strongest of the three guerrilla factions and probably tougher than the government's Soviet-supplied army `` The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> in the last three months controls much more territory than they did before,'' said <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Souen </PERSON>, a defector from the Cambodian government army.
