<HEAD>Swim Across Biblical Sea Turns Into Waterless Walk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An annual swim across the biblical Sea of <LOCATION> Galilee </LOCATION> turned into a hike on Saturday after a drop in water level forced bathers to walk the final 400 yards. About 6,000 youths began the traditional 4-mile swim from the sea's southern shore. They swam most of the way, but ended up trudging the last leg across the dried mud bottom, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said. Last winter's low rainfall has caused the sea to drop nearly 3 feet below normal. The swim took place 11 miles south of the site where many Christians believe <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> walked on the sea.
