of Soviets, Britons expelled to 11 sted 12 in penultimate graf. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> today predicted success for the sweeping reform agenda of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, saying change has gone too far to be stopped. `` I believe perestroika is now set on its course and will go through to success,'' the British leader told a news conference after four hours of talks with the Soviet president during her one-day stopover between <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The two leaders met amid reports of a breakthrough in U.S.-Soviet arms negotiations. It was their fifth meeting since <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was named <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief in 1985. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was the first major <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> leader to see <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> since this summer's wave of strikes by miners in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and flareups of ethnic violence in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. She expressed great confidence in the 58-year-old <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader and his program for economic and social reforms, saying it `` opens up vistas and horizons not available to the people of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for some 70 years.'' Asked about current domestic woes faced by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform drive, she replied, `` Anything bold and purposeful will have difficulties to it.'' One of the topics discussed by the leaders was arms control, and Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said she had been `` in touch'' with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on the matter before meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>. However, she declined to comment on anything <PERSON> Gorbachev </P