<HEAD>Remnants of Hugo Felt Over Northeast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT that today first full day of autumn,
sted equinox, which was 9:20 p.m. Friday EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The remnants of Hurricane Hugo brought thunderstorms and gusty winds over parts of the northeastern quarter of the nation early today, and officials warned of flooding from <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>. Elsewhere, a cold front settled over the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, dropping temperatures below freezing early today in some sections. Today marks the first full day of autumn in the Northern Hemisphere. The autumnal equinox, the time when the sun crosses the equator making night and day of equal length, occured at 9:20 p.m. EDT Friday. Forecasters stopped tracking <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> on Friday night as it lost the characteristics of a tropical storm. Showers and thunderstorms swept across the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the lower <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and the central Appalachians. Earlier, <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> blasted the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>. Hurricane-force winds pummeled coastal <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> around <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> early Friday. The storm's strength also was felt about 200 miles inland at <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, where nearly 3 inches of rain fell Friday, a city record for the date. More than 2 inches of rain fell at <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, and more than an inch fell at <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and Erie, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. Gusty winds were reported over a large area from <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, with gusts of 60 mph at Snowshoe, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. A flood watch was posted for today for much of western <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the Berkshires of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and the northwest hills Flash flood watches were posted in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms extended across the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the central Gulf Coast, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. Strong northwesterly winds brought cool air into the south-central states, with high winds in the middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Light snow fell across parts of northern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, and temperatures hovered around freezing in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, most of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, northern and west-central <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and much of eastern <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>. Out West, unseasonably warm weather prevailed with record high temperatures reported at a number of cities. <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> hit 91 degrees, their latest day of 90 degree weather on record. <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>' temperature soared to a record 109 degrees on Friday, while <LOCATION> Tuscon </LOCATION> sizzled at 106 degrees. It was the 90th day of 100-degree heat this year for <LOCATION> Tuscon </LOCATION>, a record. Temperature readings at 3 a.m. EDT included: EAST: <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> 75 rain; <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> 64 partly cloudy; <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> 77 windy; <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, 77 cloudy; <ORGANIZATION> Chattanooga </ORGANIZATION> 67 foggy; <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> 65 foggy; <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> 51 rain; <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> 47 windy; Key West 83 partly cloudy; <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> 75 partly cloudy; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> 75 windy; <LOCATION> P