<HEAD>Soviets Tracking Bourgeous Bucks By Evoking Imperial Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviets are making tracks to the tourist industry by building a replica of a luxurious, turn-of-the-century train that once ferried the nation's now-reviled aristocracy. Forgetting their typical disdain for the old days of czarist <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, the Soviets are planning a new Paris-to-Vladivostok train that is to feature a sauna, two dining cars and roomy passenger cars, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. Conductors also will sport czarist-era uniforms. Dubbed the <ORGANIZATION> Trans-Siberian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, the train will be pulled by steam engines along some stretches to enhance the historical experience. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not say how long the trip would last or how much it would cost. Travel time from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> is 10 to 11 days on current trains.
</TEXT>
