<HEAD>Bork Adds to Proliferation of Writings on Confirmation Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> says the conservative direction of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> with newest member <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> on board is little different from how the court would have leaned had he won confirmation instead. <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, whose appointment to a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> seat in 1987 touched off a bitter fight between liberal and conservative groups, says he has generally agreed with the justices, with just one notable exception: he would have voted to uphold a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law banning flag burning. <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> made the comments in an interview about his new book, `` The Tempting of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>: The Political Seduction of the Law,'' to be published in the next few months. Although it is not specifically about the failed nomination, a number of pages discuss the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> bid, <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> said. Other books about <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>'s fight for a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> seat also are about to roll off the presses, two years after the defeat of the conservative legal scholar. `` I just think there will be a lot of these books in the next few years _ this is one people are going to chew on for a long time,'' says conservative activist <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuigan </PERSON>, whose forthcoming book, `` The Ninth Justice: Our Fight for <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>,'' was written with <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Weyrich </PERSON>. It tells the inside story of the conservative battle to swing the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in favor of <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>. A view from the liberal side is upcoming in `` The People Rising: The Campaign Against the <ORGANIZATION> Bork </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nomination </ORGANIZATION>,'' by former <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pertschuk </PERSON> and journalist <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaetzel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>'s own book looks at the broad sweep of American history and argues that the law fell prey to politics, he said. He declined to go into much detail about the contents but said that if he had it to do over, he would change `` very little'' about his testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` What I said was what I think,'' said <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>. At a distance of two years, <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> takes his rejection by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> philosophically. `` I do n't like what happened, but do I go around being bitter? No.'' After <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>'s rejection, then-President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> nominated federal judge <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsburg </PERSON> for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> seat vacated by Justice <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ginsburg </PERSON>, however, withdrew in the midst of a furor over his earlier marijuana use. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> then nominated <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who was easily confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. One <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> book already on the shelves, `` Battle for Justice,'' by reporter <PERSON> Ethan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronner </PERSON>, recently brought a complaint from Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>. He said the book was incorrect in saying he informed the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZ