<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An army general said two men in custody have confessed to assassinating presidential candidate <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>, a killing that resulted in the government's declaration of war on drug traffickers, newspapers reported today. The reports quoted Gen. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Niebles </PERSON> as saying the army now knows who hired the two gunmen, but the newspapers said he did not say who ordered the killing or if it was drug traffickers. On Friday, the government asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> to respond to reports it has a secret list of Colombians suspected of having ties to drug lords and said such a list could damage relations between the countries. Also Friday, President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> accepted the resignation of Justice Minister <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON>, long rumored to be quitting because of death threats by cocaine traffickers. Ms. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON> said she resigned at <ORGANIZATION> Barco </ORGANIZATION>'s request. Sen. <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>, who was seeking the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s nomination for March's presidential election, was killed Aug. 18 in a hail of machine gun fire at a <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> rally. Barco blamed traffickers and declared an all-out war on them. The general's comments, at a news conference Friday in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, got front - page attention in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>'s half dozen dailies today, even though the two men in custody have not been arraigned or charged The army has a reputation of forcing confessions from people who later recant in civilian courts. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s armed forces have the authority to arrest and detain people under a state of siege that has existed in <LOCATION> Colomb