<HEAD>Industrial Nations Pressing US to Cut Budget Deficit</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS grafs 1-2 to UPDATE with start of meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Finance officials of the world's seven biggest economic powers met today amid renewed calls for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to curb the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget deficit as its contribution toward stabilizing world currency markets. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> hosted the private talks at the <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, across the street from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, with their counterparts from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> _ the so-called Group of Seven. The finance ministers and central bankers from the seven nations were expected to discuss their seeming failure to stabilize world currency markets. The dollar is trading above the targets they set despite a declaration at the officials' last meeting in April seeking no further increase. A strong dollar hurts <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to reduce its trade deficit because it raises the price of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> exports overseas and makes foreign goods cheaper in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The dollar's rise since the spring has come in the face of repeated and heavy selling by the G-7 nations' central banks in an effort to drive its value down. In advance of the session, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration insisted coordination efforts had not broken down. But officials of other nations said more was needed. Specifically, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> must reduce the demand for dollars created by its budget deficit, said a senior <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> official, speaking to reporters on condition she not be identified by name. `` One of the values of these meetings is peer pressure and the need to make the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> repeatedly aware, the administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, that the key to the imbalances problem is not some sort of exchange rate policy that brings down an overly strong dollar. ... The best way to do that is a tighter fiscal policy,'' the official said. A senior official at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged, `` We all recognize that more needs to be done. ... The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must reduce its budget deficit,'' but said that nations with trade surpluses -LRB- <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -RRB- must stimulate consumer demand at home so they are less dependent on export sales. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said if the dollar were to continue its upswing `` for a lengthy period of time, this obviously, is a matter of concern ... because obviously we have more -LRB- trade adjustments -RRB- to accomplish.'' Despite the talk before today's meeting, many private economists said they were expecting little more than vague rhetoric when the G-7 issues a communique at the end of the session. `` I would be shocked if anything really happened,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, an economic consultant in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` But I think they will reiterate the fact that stable currencies are better and that they will work together to keep the fluctuations down without saying very much about where they should go,'' Trading in currency markets Friday seemed to reflect that skepticism. The dollar rose in thin, erratic trading despite the fourth straight day of Federal Reserve dollar selling. At the end of the day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar rose to 146.05 yen from 145.65 on Thursday. The Group of Seven discussions were being held before the start of the annual meetings of the 152-nation <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and its sister lending organization, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> officials are pushing for a doubling of the fund's resources to allow it to better handle the crushing $ 1.3 trillion Third World debt burden. A senior <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> official said Friday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had not reached a conclusion that such an increase is needed.
