A presidential proclamation was quickly drafted at the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and orders were issued to send in military police to restore order. <PERSON> Farrelly </PERSON>'s request was reported to the White House by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. But the presidential order was based on a law that allows the chief executive to send in troops without a governor's request. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` was relying on his own judgment based on other reports that it was important to restore law and order,'' the official said. The decision to send in troops was made after `` federal authorities on the scene were reporting chaos, and near anarchy and the situation as being out of control,'' Admiral <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, said last week in an interview. Later Wednesday afternoon, <PERSON> Farrelly </PERSON> publicly denied that he had asked for troops. During interviews Thursday, the governor said reports of lawlessness and looting were exaggerated. He made the comments after 1,100 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops and 100 <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and deputy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals had arrived in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION>. By Friday, <PERSON> Farrelly </PERSON> had ceded all law enforcement power to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which now has comprehensive authority to make arrests and conduct prosecutions for violations of both federal and territorial law.
