<SECOND>AM-Retarded Care,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocates Aim For Further Expansion of Retarded Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates for the mentally retarded hope a judge has set an example for others around the country by ordering <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> officials to seek money to restore services for retarded Philadelphians who live at home. `` This decision is the first in the nation holding that people with retardation have a right to those services,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferleger </PERSON>, attorney for an advocacy group that joined the city in seeking the state money. The decision also marks the beginning of a move to state courts instead of federal court, where <PERSON> Ferleger </PERSON>'s group, the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Handicapped </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION>, lost earlier this year in a similar case. Commonwealth Court Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Crumlish </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> last week gave the <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> until Oct. 2 to ask the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to provide the $ 7.56 million needed for services that had been cut or canceled for up to 7,750 mentally retarded Philadelphians. The order does not cover the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, but <PERSON> Ferleger </PERSON> said if the lawmakers turn down the request, he would ask the judge to order the department to find the funds elsewhere in its budget. The judge ruled that state officials breached their responsibility under state law to assure `` adequate mental retardation services for all persons who need them.'' <PERSON> Crumlish </PERSON>'s opinion took state officials to task for failing to evaluate the needs of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s mentally retarded in coming up with a budget. Instead, the state just added a little more to what had been budgeted before, whether that previous amount met actual needs. The ruling dealt only with the state's handling of one county. But `` that thing will be widely disseminated,'' said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergman </PERSON>, deputy director for governmental activities for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cerebral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palsy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associations </ORGANIZATION>. `` I would suggest there are other parties in other states where they have similar grounds under their state laws,'' <PERSON> Bergman </PERSON> said. `` Very few states base their budgets on actual client need. That issue will be true everywhere,'' <PERSON> Ferleger </PERSON> said. A 1987 survey by the Association for Retarded Citizens found 76,000 people waiting for day programs around the country. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gold </PERSON>, deputy city solicitor for <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, is n't convinced of a national effect of <PERSON> Crumlish </PERSON>'s ruling `` Our lawsuit is under state law,'' he said simply. However, state law is becoming the chosen legal strategy as groups push for services to keep people out of institutions, integrate them into society and help them do things for themselves. The move to state courts began with a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in February that held the state of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> did not have a constitutional duty to protect a boy who suffered brain damage from repeated beatings by his father. <PERSON> Ferleger </PERSON>'s group won an initial victory in federal court on rights for the retarded to community services under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution. But the 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reversed the case, citing the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> ruling as grounds. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, the state public advocate has sued the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in state court, contending the agency was n't providing appropriate community services to about 3,300 people. `` In recent years the federal Constitution has been interpreted increasingly narrowly on disabilities issues. And some of the state constitutions have been providing greater protection,'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Headley </PERSON>, an attorney for the public advocate. Advocates like to see efforts succeed in other states. `` It's always important that some other judge somewhere else was willing to do this,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischner </PERSON>, attorney for the Center for Public Representation in <LOCATION> Northampton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tannis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for Law in the Public Interest, said her group won a ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that state law required community treatment for the chronically mentally ill. A national solution could come from outside the courts The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in the next two weeks may consider a bill sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION>, and co-sponsored by 53 others, that would eventually make such services a federal right _ the way <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> mandated in 1975 that disabled children have a right to go to school.
