<HEAD>New York's Museum of Modern Art to Open Picasso-Braque Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just how <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON> and his lesser-known friend <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Braque </PERSON> invented cubism eight decades ago is the topic of a major exhibit opening Sunday at the Museum of Modern Art. The show, described by the museum as the first attempt to examine cubism `` through an in-depth concentration on its core,'' deals with the artists' work between 1907 and 1914. `` During the cubist years both artists were at their best when they were closest to one another,'' exhibition organizer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> writes in the catalog. `` Cubism as we know it was a vision that neither artist could have realized alone.'' A <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> critic described the exhibit as `` the show of the decade.'' The exhibition consists of 390 works, including paintings, drawings, prints, sculptures and collages. They were borrowed from museums and collections all over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The French-born <PERSON> Braque </PERSON> lived from 1882 to 1963. <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> who spent most of his life in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, lived from 1881 to 1973. They were colleagues in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> at the time they developed the abstract style known as cubism in the early years of the century.
