<DATELINE>JACKSON HOLE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flashing the thumbs-up sign, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> today moved through the final rounds of talks to put the finishing touches on a series of arms control agreements. The most significant step was the Soviets' dropping their insistence that curbs on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Star Wars missile defense be completed before a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty. That appeared to break an impasse over talks to slash long-range nuclear weapons arsenals, said a senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official. A senior official traveling with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> are expected to announce that a summit will be held within the first six months of 1990, mostly likely in the spring. The two both flashed the thumbs-up sign as they strolled briefly through the woods before resuming their discussions. `` We are working very hard,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. The announcement that the Soviets had dropped a major demand came Friday night as <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> also neared agreement on an accord to open each other's underground nuclear tests to on-site inspection. The foreign ministers began their final talks at a Rocky Mountain lodge today, with expectations high that they would set a target date for a summit between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The foreign secretaries also made progress toward several other arms control agreements they were expected to sign before heading to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Sunday for a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> meeting. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCAT