e from emigration issues to cover revisions in the Soviet criminal code, occupational health and the environment _ A pact to lift the so-called `` Ice Curtain'' that since 1948 has prevented Alaskan Eskimos from visiting their distant relations in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> Despite the friendly atmosphere, the two sides remained divided over the major negotiation before them, START. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> presented the Americans with what one Soviet official called `` exhilarating'' proposals to clear a main obstacle to START, an agreement on adherence to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. That pact curbs development of space-based defenses such as the Strategic Defense Initiative, as the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> plan is formally known. The proposals dealt with space tests of potential weapons, but <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> negotiators said they did not mark a sharp departure from previous Soviet ideas. A senior <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said most of the Baker-Shevardnadze session was devoted to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> complaints that the Soviets were boosting military shipments to allies involved in wars in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Asked whether <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> promised to curtail the arms flow, the official said, `` Each side has a more complete understanding of some of the other's concerns.'' Disagreement over regional conflicts, however, likely would be overshadowed by the five agreements. Under the protocol on testing-site inspections, Soviet inspectors would monitor the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> test site and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors would observe tests in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors using a system known as CORRTEX would be notified in advance of a test explosion at the Soviets' Semipalatinsk site. They would drop a cable into a nearby four-foot-wide hole. The force of the explosion would be measured by the speed at which the cable was smashed. Under the 1974 and 1976 treaties, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet underground nuclear blasts _ the only kind not outlawed _ are limited to 150 kilotons.
