law; I believe it's constitutional,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said, adding that he did not believe the plaintiffs had tried to use all legal procedures outlined in the law. Cooperating in the lawsuit is Planned Parenthood of <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION>, which offers abortion counseling. Another plaintiff is Dr. <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Stover </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, who performs abortions. `` Parental notice is unjustified because it increases the medical risk to the teen-ager,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Libbe </PERSON>, a Planned Parenthood spokeswoman. The lawsuit contends that the law places an undue burden on the teen-ager's right to an abortion, and an excessive burden on either the teen-ager or the doctor in locating both parents. There is an exception if the whereabouts of one of the parents is unknown. In addition, the law is so vague that a physician could be subject to criminal penalties, yet can not understand what the law requires of him, the lawsuit said.
