<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On Folly Beach, a house sat in the road; in some places, houses had disappeared. And on <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and the Isle of Palms, Hurricane Hugo had damaged virtually every building, an aerial tour showed Saturday. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> tore a wide path along the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast, but areas less than 20 miles from some of the worst-hit areas appeared unscathed. About 680,000 people live along <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s 220 miles of coast. Over <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Head </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and, about 150 miles to the south, over the islands of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fripp </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, there were few telltale signs of Friday's storm aside from boarded-up houses and trees on the ground. <LOCATION> Edisto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, just south of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, suffered serious erosion when water rushed over the road and under most seaward houses, many of which rest on supports. No homes were leveled, however. But heading north, a band of devastation stretched for 90 miles from <LOCATION> Folly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, five miles southeast of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. As many as 30 percent of the homes on Folly Beach had either disappeared or were uninhabitable, and it appeared that all the others had suffered some damage from the rains and wind above 100 mph. One house had been tossed onto a road. From the air above <LOCATION> James </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> suburb that lies on the inland side of Folly Beach, most of the roads and homes could be seen in areas that once were hidden by thick woods. But the damage to buildings was less than on Folly Beach. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s Island and the Isle of Palms bore the brunt of <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s fury, and every structure on both islands appeared damaged Many houses were buckled and had their supports ripped away, and sometimes nothing was left but a roof or pilings in the sand. Several houses were in roads, roofs were peeled off, and trees were uprooted. The <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridge </PERSON>, the swing bridge that links the two islands to the mainland, was twisted and tilted so that one end dipped 35 feet down to the Intracoastal Waterway. At the Wild Dunes marina on the Isle of Palms, about 40 boats were blown across the shore and heaped into a pile. At Folly Beach, other boats were stacked up between a bridge and condominium project. Just to the north, homes in the Bull's <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> area also were heavily damaged, and a marina in <LOCATION> Winyah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Georgetown </LOCATION> had disappeared. Massive oceanfront homes in the wealthy residential community of <LOCATION> Debidue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> fell from their pilings to the surf, and wind had ripped off the fronts of houses, exposing rooms. More than three-quarters of the homes were damaged. On <PERSON> Pawley </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, at least three homes were across or in the creek that separates the island from the mainland. Some had been moved more than 100 yards. A channel of water approximately 20 feet wide had sliced the island in two. Roads in <PERSON> Pawley </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> were covered with sand as far as three blocks from the beach. <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> suffered severe erosion that exposed brown soil beneath the beach sand, but wind damage was minor. And an amusement park roller coaster appeared intact.
