<HEAD>Azerbaijan Declares Itself Sovereign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> on Saturday became the latest <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> republic to declare itself `` sovereign,'' meaning decrees from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> do n't have to be obeyed if they conflict with local law, local journalists reported. The vote by the Supreme Soviet parliament in the mostly Moslem republic in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> also indirectly reasserts <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>'s right to rule <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> and Armenian enclave that has belonged to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> since the 1920s <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> put <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> under its direct administration in February because of ethnic violence that has now lasted for 19 months. But the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> parliament earlier this month rejected that step as an infringement on its right to govern territory granted it by the Soviet Constitution. The law on sovereignty approved Saturday by the republic's Supreme Soviet establishes the `` integrity, indivisibility and inviolability'' of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>'s territory, said <PERSON> Arif </PERSON> <PERSON> Aliev </PERSON>, an independent journalist He spoke by telephone from <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, the republic's capital. <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> also was declared `` independent'' in all matters except those it delegates voluntarily to national authorities in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Aliev </PERSON> said. The parliament reportedly rejected as illegal an assembly of ethnic Armenians from <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> who in August again voted to secede from <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and join <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> was the first of the 15 Soviet republics to challenge <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s rule by declaring the republic `` sovereign'' last November. The <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership immediately rejected the move as unconstitutional, but government and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> policy have since been altered to give more powers to the republics. Since President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to power in 1985, ethnic regions throughout their nation have increasingly asserted their independence and embraced their nationalist heritage, outgrowths of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s more open society.
