<HEAD>Historical District, Buildings Battered But Not Broken By Hugo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This 319-year-old city suffered some damage from Hurricane Hugo to its wealth of historic buildings and sites, but history was on its side. The most famous monument, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sumter </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, where the first shots of the Civil War were fired, suffered about $ 1 million in damage to tourist areas but was mostly intact, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, will send representatives to <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> to assess the damage to historic buildings, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyt </PERSON>, an official with the group, said Saturday. The organization was worried that <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> had dealt a major blow to the nation's architectural history, but early reports indicated a remarkable lack of damage, she said. No other city has as many historic landmarks, Ms. <PERSON> Hoyt </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>'s historic district is home to about 2,000 buildings, including 73 built before the Revolutionary War. Among them are the <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> plantation, set on a bluff over the <LOCATION> Ashley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, northwest of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, which was built in the 1730s. The plantation house, a two-story red brick building with white columns, suffered some water and wind damage but apparently is structurally sound, Ms. <PERSON> Hoyt </PERSON> said. The city's elegant Battery district, an area of palatial 2-century-old homes that look through massive oaks draped with Spanish moss to <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> beyond, are still occupied by families. A walking tour Saturday found many missing shingles and shutters _ and countless shredded oak trees _ but the Colonial and Georgian mansions stood unbroken. Broken oak trees damaged some formal gardens and blocked some streets. `` We have seen lots of roof damage, lots of fallen trees and lots of garden walls knocked down,'' said <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Charleston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. `` There is a great deal of mud and water on the first floors of some of the houses on the Battery, but fortunately there appears to be little structural damage.'' `` This house has been here for 269 years,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCrady </PERSON>, who along with his neighbors was cleaning up <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s mess Saturday. `` We just lost a few slates off the roof.'' <PERSON> McCrady </PERSON>'s house was built in 1730 by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bull </PERSON>, who later became the lieutenant governor of the colony of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> for the British. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, a history professor at <ORGANIZATION> Charleston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, said most of the oldest city structures had already withstood a furious hurricane in the late 1750s as well as the famous 1886 earthquake that destroyed dozens of lesser buildings. `` The oldest buildings we have were designed to withstand storms, and the ones that are left have been through this before,'' <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said. `` But I'd say there has n't been a storm of this magnitude for 200 years.'' Two-foot-thick walls, raised foundations and sturdy storm shutters all are staples of the old structures, <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said _ safeguards not found in newer buildings that in some cases crumbled like matchsticks under <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s force.
