 Terrified by a new wave of political violence, the family of an abducted human rights activist fled this country Saturday after spending nearly six weeks holed up in a room at the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumalda </PERSON> <PERSON> Camey </PERSON>'s husband, her two babies, her brother and his family left for <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> under Spanish diplomatic protection. They were following six other relatives who were granted political asylum by <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> last week. `` It is incredible how this family has been persecuted,'' Angel <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Figueroa </PERSON>, the deputy federal attorney general for human rights, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Their flight began Aug. 15, when armed men burst into the activist's modest home in <LOCATION> Esquintla </LOCATION> province at 5 a.m. and dragged her off. `` I heard the shots and the screams. It was her. Kidnapped,'' said her husband, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Camey </PERSON>, who was interviewed last week in the crowded room where he and his family had taken refuge. His 23-year-old wife was the fourth person in her family to disappear in 10 months. The others eventually turned up _ all shot dead and dumped on roadsides. Camey, a 23-year-old farmer, does n't believe his wife survived either Under the rightist generals who ruled in the early 1980s, tens of thousands of Guatemalans died or disappeared, including <PERSON> Camey </PERSON>'s father His wife has been a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Support </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, an organization made up of relatives of the missing. Human rights groups put the toll of dead and disappeared as a result of activities of right-wing death squads at 40,000. They say many of the squads were linked to the army or other security forces. Tens of thousands of others have been displaced, fleeing the military's scorched earth campaign against leftist guerrillas in the countryside. After his wife was abducted, <PERSON> Camey </PERSON>'s family and his brother-in-law's family, fearing for their own safety, sought refuge at Mutual Support's office in the capital of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> 30 miles away. About thirty minutes after they arrived, a grenade was lobbed through the window. They were evacuated to the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, where they remained for nearly six weeks. With the advent of civilian rule three years ago, human rights abuses began to abate. But in the last two months, there has been a surge of killings and bombings. Bodies have been found along the roads, their hands cut off. Fear has returned. `` <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> is returning to the bloody times,'' <PERSON> Camey </PERSON> said, cradling his children. `` There is terrible violence, not just in my home, but in many homes.'' Human rights workers blame the latest violence on right-wing extremists who believe that President <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON>'s rule is too liberal. <ORGANIZATION> Cerezo </ORGANIZATION>, who has survived two coup attempts, has denied any security forces are involved in the current violence.
