<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials declared a forest disaster in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> on Saturday after <PERSON> Hurricane </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> left half the state's 43 counties with extensive or moderate timber damage. `` It certainly is one of the worst forest disasters that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> has seen in many, many years,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, a forester with the state <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The storm, which came ashore near <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> packing sustained winds of 135 mph, tore a path across <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s coast early Friday. Although its strength was dissipated once it hit land, <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> uprooted trees and broke limbs as it quickly moved north into <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Extensive timber damage, defined as an area that will require a great deal of salvage, occurred in nine counties on or near the coast. Moderate timber damage _ requiring some salvage _ occurred in 12 counties, and all the rest of the state's counties suffered light timber damage, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. Forestry is the third-largest manufacturing industry in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, generating $ 4.3 billion annually and employing more than 30,000. Seventy-five state personnel were surveying damage in the hardest-hit areas Saturday, and 35 tractors were brought in to help salvage efforts, he said. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said he could not yet estimate the cost of the damage, and it was still too early to develop a replanting plan or ask for relief aid, he said. `` We will be working with all the private landowners in trying to salvage the material,'' he added. `` It's going to be a big job.''
