<HEAD>Pope Calls for Increased Anti-Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCCA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> called Saturday for increased national and international efforts to fight the drug trade but said addicts should be treated with compassion. `` The various public institutions, on the national and international level, are called on to put a brake to the expansion of the market of narcotics substances,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said during a visit to a drug rehabilitation clinic on his three-day tour of <LOCATION> Tuscany </LOCATION> in nordhern Irtaly. `` The interests that gain financially from such a trade must be brought to light,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said. `` Then the instruments and mechanisms they use must be identified, and finally one will proceed to their coordinated and efficient dismantling.'' The pope, without mentioning any countries by name, said there is a need to promote development in those regions where residents depend on production of drugs for their livelihood. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> also praised the work of rehabilitation clinics and social programs that offer addicts `` alternative models of life'' to lead them away from drugs and reintegrate them into society. `` Drugs are fought not only by health and judicial means but also _ and especially _ by installing new human relationships, rich in spiritual and tender values,'' he said. The <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said drug abuse is a `` clear symptom of a society that no longer succeeds in living true values and pushes those who use -LRB- drugs -RRB- into egoism and solitude.'' `` In this climate, the goals to pursue become money, power, career, consumer goods. One is ready to pay whatever price to obtain them,'' he said.
