<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday enacted an emergency ordinance barring price-gouging in this hurricane-ravaged city, where 5-pound bags of ice were being sold for $ 10 and long lines snaked outside stores that opened. `` It would be an unfair trade practice to charge something higher than pre-hurricane prices,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who called for the emergency legislation the council passed in a vote by telephone. `` If I hear of the instance of someone doing that, not only will they be arrested, but I will personally take pleasure in participating in the arrest,'' <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said. Violators would be subjected to fines of $ 200 and jail terms of 30 days. The emergency ordinance is in effect until commerce returns to normal, <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said. Authorities reported that gas at some locations was selling for $ 3 to $ 4.50 a gallon. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> cited the instance of ice being sold for $ 10. The state <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> requested that merchants charge no more than $ 2 a bag. `` There is a problem with gouging,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the state Emergency Preparedness Division. Long lines flowed from stores that managed to open Saturday, partly because police asked that no more than 10 people be allowed in stores at any one time. <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, manager of a Food Lion grocery store in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> that suffered only a few damaged ceiling tiles, said `` a couple of thousand'' customers showed up Saturday before the store was forced to close because it had no lights. Lines `` were going out the parking lot and into the street,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said. `` It takes them about four hours to get into the store. `` It was hairy at times but it worked out all right,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said. `` It was hot and people were irritated _ others were cutting in line.'' Cashiers used pocket calculators. People bought `` anything they could get their hands on,'' he said. And trucks outside gave dry ice to people, he said. A crowd hoping to get ice in the parking lot at the Citadel Mall started pushing and shoving and police were called, but there were no injuries or arrests, Maj. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiley </PERSON> said. `` Frankly, some people were panicking over ice,'' <PERSON> Wiley </PERSON> said, noting that food could begin spoiling after two days without electricity. `` It was n't a riot, but it could have been,'' said Police Lt. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>, one of the first officers on the scene. `` There was some pushing and shoving, cursing, just some hot tempers.'' At another mall, motorists turned one lane of a road into a parking lot when they jumped out of their cars to get ice that was being given out. The city has been without electricity since Thursday, when Hurricane Hugo toppled power lines in much of the state, leaving hundreds of thousands of people without power. Restoring electricity `` may take a very long time,'' <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said. `` There's no electricity coming into the transmission lines and the generating capacity down here is gone.'' Utility crews from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> have been sent to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> to help, he said. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said the city surveyed 2,000 buildings, one-third the total in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, and found 24 in varying degrees of collapse. He said there also were a number of collapsed chimneys in danger of sliding off sloped roofs and `` extraordinary'' tree damage in the city. Despite the difficulties, the mayor said he was inspired by the spirit in which <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> residents endured the hardships. `` Throughout the city today, people are upbeat and they are thankful,'' he said. `` They're thankful they're alive and that the city is essentially intact.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> expects Hurricane Hugo relief efforts to be the costliest in the organization's history, a spokesman said Saturday. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Langston </PERSON>, assistant director of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, said the storm will cost the agency an estimated $ 38 million. `` We estimate that more than 73,000 people have received assistance to date, and this is just the beginning,'' <PERSON> Langston </PERSON> said at a news conference. More than 150 volunteers and paid disaster specialists will be brought into <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION> and other affected areas, he said.
